            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Abstract—Resonant accelerometers are very attractive for high-precision measurement applications due to their high sensitivity, frequency output, and large dynamic range. In order to further increase their sensitivity, we propose a novel method to enhance sensitivity of MEMS resonant accelerometer by using electrostatic spring softening effect. The sensitivity is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "691\\mathrm{Hz / g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " boosted up  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "60\\%"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " higher than the original sensitivity and the nonlinearity is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.5\\%"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", comparing to the original nonlinearity is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.4\\%"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " in preliminary tests. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                306,
                486,
                425
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Keywords—MEMS, Resonant Accelerometer, Enhance Sensitivity, Electrostatic Spring "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                436,
                486,
                465
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "I. INTRODUCTION "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                210,
                481,
                339,
                494
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "MEMS (Micro-electro-mechanical systems) acceleration sensors have been widely used in the fields of automotive, consumer electronics and aerospace, due to the mature fabrication, low cost and massive production[1-3]. Their sensing principle includes resonance, piezoresistance, capacitance and so on. Among of them, resonant accelerometers, based on the resonant frequency shift of the resonator under axial loading, are very attractive for high precision measurement applications because of their high sensitivity, frequency output, and large dynamic range[1,2]. The sensitivity is one of critical metrics in micromachined resonant acceleration sensors. In order to increase the sensitivity, using the mechanical micro-levers is a well-known method in MEMS resonant accelerometers [1, 3-6], and lower effective spring stiffness of suspension structure on the sensitive axis is preferred for high amplification ratio levers [6]. However, reducing the effective spring stiffness on sensitive axis is restricted in real devices due to the trade-offs for the cross-axis sensitivity, robustness and fabrication yield. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                500,
                486,
                763
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "In order to solve this problem and further enhance sensitivity, this paper uses electrostatic spring softening effect to further improve the sensitivity. The prototype device is designed and analysed. Then both of the simulation and experimental results of the prototype device are presented to verify the proposed sensitivity enhancement method. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                768,
                486,
                853
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "II. DESIGN AND SIMULATION "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                614,
                316,
                813,
                330
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The schematic view of the sensitivity enhancing structure for resonant accelerometer is shown in Figure 1(a). The proof mass is connected to the resonator by micro-levers to amplify the acceleration induced inertial force and axially apply on the resonators. As a result, the resonant frequencies of the resonators at both sides of the proof mass change differentially due to the axial force changing their stiffness. The difference of these two frequencies is, to the first order, proportional to the input acceleration. Four pairs of back-to-back parallel plate electrostatic actuators on proof mass are used to soften the mass-suspended effective spring in order to further improve the sensitivity, called sensitivity enhancing structure. Four pairs of the comb tuning structures are used to zero the electrostatic force in the case of the parallel plate capacitors are unsymmetrical due to fabrication tolerance, called tuning structure. The structure design parameters of the prototype device are summarized in the table 1. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                506,
                335,
                928,
                571
            ]
        },
